{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5036a04f-a9ff-4f94-a04c-180eedd44867","content":"## What's Happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level**, most likely from **x86-64-v2** to **x86-64-v3**. Your 2012-era hardware (likely Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge) doesn't meet the new baseline.\n\n### The x86-64 microarchitecture levels:\n\n| Level | Key Instructions | First CPUs | Year |\n|-------|-----------------|------------|------|\n| **v1** | SSE2 | Original x86-64 | 2003 |\n| **v2** | SSE4.2, POPCNT, SSSE3 | Nehalem/Westmere | ~2008 |\n| **v3** | **AVX2**, FMA, BMI1/2 | **Haswell** | **2013** |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | Skylake-X | 2017 |\n\nYour 2012 hardware supports up to **v2** (Sandy/Ivy Bridge have AVX but **not AVX2**), so it passed .NET 10's v2 baseline but fails .NET 11's v3 requirement.\n\n### Your other platforms are unaffected:\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)** — different architecture, has its own Arm64 baseline\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72)** — also Arm64, not subject to x86-64 levels\n\n### Options:\n1. **Replace the 2012 hardware** with Haswell (2013) or newer CPUs\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** for those specific nodes (it's an LTS release)\n3. Check if the runtime supports a `DOTNET_EnableAVX2=0`-style env var to fall back to software paths (historically limited support for this)\n\nYou can verify what a node supports by checking `/proc/cpuinfo` for the `avx2` flag:\n```bash\ngrep -o 'avx2' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90db4f37-5a31-41bb-b156-76c1c434e70a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a known issue I can explain from my knowledge.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, let me think more carefully...\n\nActually, let me reconsider the timeline. The user says they're upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is set in 2026, so these would be future versions. Let me think about what's actually known:\n\n\nI'm trying to recall the exact timeline for when Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline requirements. .NET 8 introduced environment variables for controlling SSE support, and .NET 9 made changes to the baseline, but I need to be precise about which version raised it to v2 and what that entails.\n\nLooking at the specifics: x86-64-v2 requires CMPXCHG16B, LAHF/SAHF, POPCNT, and SSE3 through SSE4.2. Hardware from around 2011-2012 like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge generally supports these features, though some older Atom processors from that era might not have full v2 support.\n\nThe user's situation makes sense if .NET 10 was already enforcing the v2 baseline (which their 2012 hardware could handle), but .NET 11 raised it to v3. The v3 level adds AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, LZCNT, and MOVBE—features that Sandy Bridge lacks since it only has basic AVX support. This would explain why upgrading to .NET 11 broke compatibility with their older hardware. which means Sandy Bridge (2011) wouldn't have v2 support. So if .NET 11 raised the baseline to v2 or higher, that would explain why their 2012 hardware is failing—it's right on the edge of what's supported, and older chips in that generation lack the required instruction sets. The other platforms like Windows Arm64 and Raspberry Pi 4 use different architectures, so they're not affected by x86-64 baseline changes. I need to be careful here since .NET 11 is a future version, but I recall that .NET 9 raised the Linux x86-64 baseline to require SSE3, SSSE3, and SSE4.1, so the most likely scenario is that .NET 11 pushed the baseline even further to AVX2, which the 2012 hardware doesn't support.","outputTokens":2208,"requestId":"300F:1031D7:167AF55:193B97F:6A067ADB"},"id":"f45212b6-cfe8-4747-a4ae-6e8673c256d9","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:46:47.271Z","pare